(33331, 2, 1478, 'There are many factors that can increase a drivers level of fatigue. They include:\n Eating heavy foods.\n Working long hours.\n Drinking alcohol.\n Taking medication, especially if mixed with alcohol.', 'en', 'MM'),
(33332, 2, 1479, 'Drowsy drivers may fall asleep and not even know it. They may experience microsleeps, which are sleep episodes lasting from a fraction of a second to several seconds. One of the symptoms of microsleeps is gaps in awareness. Considering that a vehicle traveling at 100 km/h covers almost 30 meters in one second, it is easy to see how a brief gap in awareness could turn into a fatal crash.', 'en', 'MM'),
(33333, 2, 1262, 'Fatigue vs. Alcohol', 'en', 'MM'),
(33334, 2, 1480, 'Lack of sleep can make drivers as dangerous on the road as drunk drivers. If you drive after being awake for 17 hours, you have roughly the same crash risk as a driver with a blood alcohol content of 0.05%. If you extend your awake time to 24 hours, you are as likely to crash as a driver with a BAC of 0.10%.', 'en', 'MM'),
