(1288, 498, 2, 'Drowsy Driving', 1),
(1289, 498, 3, 'In this module, participants will learn:\n1.  The dangers of fatigued driving.  \n2.  How drowsy driving is impaired driving.\n3.  Techniques to help drivers avoid fatigue-related crashes.', 1),
(1290, 499, 2, 'Fatigue Kills', 1),
(1291, 499, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/DRW/Global/Slides/IMG02.svg', 1),
(1292, 499, 3, 'Few driving concerns are as common or as dangerous as fatigue. Tired drivers have slower perception times, have impaired judgment and vision, and pay less attention to the actions of other drivers. In the worst cases, fatigued drivers drift from their lane or drive off the road, ending in serious injury or death. Drowsiness is a factor in many fatal crashes in Asia.', 1),
(1293, 500, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/DRW/Global/Slides/IMG03.svg', 1),
(1294, 500, 2, 'Factors Increasing Tiredness', 1),
(1295, 500, 3, 'There are many factors that can increase a drivers level of fatigue. They include:\n Eating heavy foods.\n Working long hours.\n Drinking alcohol.\n Taking medication, especially if mixed with alcohol.', 1),
(1296, 501, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/DRW/Global/Slides/IMG04.svg', 1),
(1297, 501, 3, 'Drowsy drivers may fall asleep and not even know it. They may experience microsleeps, which are sleep episodes lasting from a fraction of a second to several seconds. One of the symptoms of microsleeps is gaps in awareness. Considering that a vehicle traveling at 100 km/h covers almost 30 meters in one second, it is easy to see how a brief gap in awareness could turn into a fatal crash.', 1),
(1298, 501, 2, 'Dangerous Microsleeps', 1),
(1299, 502, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/DRW/Global/Slides/IMG05.svg', 1),
(1300, 502, 2, 'Fatigue vs. Alcohol', 1),
(1301, 502, 3, 'Lack of sleep can make drivers as dangerous on the road as drunk drivers. If you drive after being awake for 17 hours, you have roughly the same crash risk as a driver with a blood alcohol content of 0.05%. If you extend your awake time to 24 hours, you are as likely to crash as a driver with a BAC of 0.10%.', 1),
(1302, 503, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/global/slides/IMG06.svg', 1),
(1303, 503, 2, 'Under the Influence of Fatigue', 1),
(1304, 503, 3, 'Drowsy drivers make dangerous mistakes such as:\n Failing to maintain a steady and appropriate speed.\n Drifting from lane to lane.\n Following vehicles too closely.\n Missing traffic signs and exits.', 1),
(1305, 504, 12, 'Run Off the Road by Fatigue', 1),
(1306, 504, 14, 'Sleepy drivers are up to 3 times more likely to crash off the road than non-drowsy drivers.', 1),
