(1635, 631, 2, 'Escape Routes', 1),
(1636, 631, 3, 'In this module, participants will learn:\n1.  The risks of driving without escape routes.\n2.  Common errors that trap drivers in traffic.\n3.  Techniques to create and maintain escape routes.', 1),
(1637, 632, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/ESR/Global/Slides/IMG02.svg', 1),
(1638, 631, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/ESR/Global/Slides/IMG01.svg', 1),
(1639, 632, 2, 'Emergencies Appear Suddenly', 1),
(1640, 632, 3, 'The variety of hazards on the road is endless; almost anything can happen at almost any moment. It is impossible to anticipate every mistake a driver could make or every mechanical emergency that could occur. Without an escape route, a driver could be left with nowhere to go and no time to respond in a crisis. ', 1),
(1641, 633, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/ESR/Global/Slides/IMG03.svg', 1),
(1642, 633, 2, 'Seconds Count', 1),
(1643, 633, 3, 'Drivers may feel that they have enough space ahead to stop safely in an emergency, but the facts may contradict this confidence. It takes drivers one to four seconds just to identify a hazard ahead and move the foot to the brake pedal. At 100 km/h a vehicle travels between 28 and 112 meters in this time before the brakes are even engaged.', 1),
(1644, 634, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/ESR/Global/Slides/IMG04.svg', 1),
(1645, 634, 2, 'Trapped in Traffic ', 1),
(1646, 634, 3, 'Boxed-in drivers are helpless, forced to trust their lives to the driving skills of those around them. They cannot avoid aggressive drivers or accommodate the mistakes of those who are distracted or fatigued. Other motorists may overreact to small hazards, creating further emergencies. When drivers are trapped in traffic, the risk of being involved in a nearby collision increases.', 1),
(1647, 635, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/ESR/Global/Slides/IMG05.svg', 1),
(1648, 635, 2, 'Mistakes That Trap Drivers', 1),
(1649, 635, 3, 'These common errors often contribute to a driver becoming trapped:\n Failing to maintain a safe following distance.\n Failing to scan and monitor traffic at all points around the vehicle.\n Failing to check blind spots regularly.\n Encroaching on other drivers escape routes.', 1),
(1650, 636, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/global/slides/IMG06.svg', 1),
(1651, 636, 2, 'Watch Your Space', 1),
(1652, 636, 3, 'Use these techniques to establish and maintain escape routes around your vehicle:\n Monitor traffic in all directions.\n Scan constantly for hazards farther ahead.\n Respect the space and escape routes of other drivers.\n Consciously plan your escape routes as you drive. You should always have an answer to this question: What would I do if something happened right now?\n', 1),
