(1995, 769, 3, 'In this module, participants will learn:\n1.     Why intersections are dangerous.\n2.     Common mistakes drivers make in intersections.\n3.     Techniques to navigate intersections safely.\n', 1),
(1996, 770, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/JCT/Global/Slides/IMG02.svg', 1),
(1997, 770, 2, 'High Traffic Interaction', 1),
(1998, 770, 3, 'In an intersection, motorists, cyclists and pedestrians all cross paths at different speeds and from different directions in a tight space. The variety of signs, signals and road markings also can be overwhelming and distracting. The resulting confusion is often deadly: At least 1 out of 5 traffic fatalities occurs at an intersection.', 1),
(1999, 771, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/JCT/Global/Slides/IMG03.svg', 1),
(2000, 771, 2, 'Intersections Are Misunderstood', 1),
(2001, 771, 3, 'A four-way intersection with traffic signals is what many people think of as an intersection, but roundabouts, T-junctions, staggered crossings, driveways meeting roads, and crosswalks are all examples as well. Anywhere two or more roads intersect, the crash risk increases.', 1),
(2002, 772, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/JCT/Global/Slides/IMG04.svg', 1),
(2003, 772, 2, 'Uncontrollable Hazards', 1),
(2004, 772, 3, 'An intersections hazards are often magnified by factors outside a drivers control. Adverse weather can greatly increase a vehicles stopping distance. Parked vehicles, the landscape and roadwork can obscure sightlines, and other road users may act in unexpected or dangerous ways. Up to 50% of collisions with pedestrians and cyclists, the most vulnerable road users, occur at intersections.', 1),
(2005, 773, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/JCT/Global/Slides/IMG05.svg', 1),
(2006, 773, 2, 'Common Driver Mistakes', 1),
(2007, 773, 3, 'The following driver mistakes are responsible for many common intersection collisions:\n Running red or yellow lights.\n Signaling late or not signaling at all.\n Changing lanes at the last moment or inside the intersection.\n Forgetting to check for other road users in blind spots.\n', 1),
(2008, 774, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/global/slides/IMG06.svg', 1),
(2009, 774, 2, 'Navigating Intersections Safely', 1),
(2010, 774, 3, 'Here are some essential techniques to reduce the risk when navigating an intersection:\n  Scan constantly for hazards.\n  Cover the brake pedal with your foot, and be prepared to stop if necessary.\n  Signal and change lanes well in advance of the intersection.\n  Be patient. Do not enter an intersection until you are sure that you can exit safely. \n', 1),
