(2174, 838, 2, 'Proper Lane Changes and Mirrors', 1),
(2175, 838, 3, 'In this module, participants will learn:\n1.  Common mistakes drivers make when changing lanes.\n2.  How to maximize the view around a vehicle.\n3.  How to practice proper lane discipline.\n', 1),
(2176, 839, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/LNC/Global/Slides/IMG02.svg', 1),
(2177, 839, 2, 'Common Mistakes, Disastrous Consequences', 1),
(2178, 839, 3, 'When drivers ignore safe lane discipline, they make roads dangerous for everyone. Collisions often occur when drivers fail to signal or monitor traffic, or when they practice poor space management while merging into a new lane. Unsafe lane changes cause crashes every day in Asia, and some motorists only recognize their mistake after it is too late.', 1),
(2179, 840, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/LNC/Global/Slides/IMG03.svg', 1),
(2180, 840, 2, 'Mixed Signals', 1),
(2181, 840, 3, 'Anticipating driver behavior is difficult enough, and improper signaling makes it worse. Whenever drivers change lanes, they enter a part of the road that belongs to road users already using it. By signaling too soon, too late or not at all, drivers create uncertainty in traffic and become a hazard to those around them.', 1),
(2182, 841, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/LNC/Global/Slides/IMG04.svg', 1),
(2183, 841, 2, 'Turning a Blind Eye', 1),
(2184, 841, 3, 'Blind spots are hidden areas around the vehicle that go unseen in the mirrors, and activity in them can change quickly. Overlapping mirrors duplicate views, while turning them too wide expands blind spots and forces drivers to glance over their shoulder more often, taking their eyes off the road ahead.\n \nOccupying blind spots exposes motorists to blind maneuvers taken by other vehicles, especially large trucks.', 1),
(2185, 842, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/LNC/Global/Slides/IMG05.svg', 1),
(2186, 842, 2, 'Poor Space Management', 1),
(2187, 842, 3, 'Changing lanes is always risky, and poor space management during a lane change violates the right-of-way of other motorists. Drivers who tailgate, pass unsafely or weave through traffic save little time, and they elevate their crash risk. Aggressive driving causes many fatal crashes on Asian roads every year.', 1),
(2188, 843, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/global/slides/IMG06.svg', 1),
(2189, 843, 2, 'Lane Change Discipline', 1),
(2190, 843, 3, 'The following techniques will help you change lanes safely:\n  Adjusting your mirrors for the best possible view before heading out.\n  Maintaining the space around your vehicle that other vehicles should not enter.\n  Establishing a safe distance behind a vehicle before passing it.\n  Signaling properly, and checking your mirrors and blind spots at every stage of a lane change.\n  Avoiding lane changes whenever possible.\n', 1),
(2191, 844, 12, 'Caught by Surprise', 1),
(2192, 844, 14, 'Up to 75% of lane-change crashes include the driver failing to see the crash hazard in time.', 1),
