(2361, 911, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/LTR/Global/Slides/IMG01.svg', 1),
(2362, 911, 2, 'Sharing the Road With Large Trucks', 1),
(2363, 911, 3, 'In this module, participants will learn:\n1.    The dangers posed by large trucks.\n2.    How to avoid a trucks blind spots.\n3.    How to share the road safely with large vehicles.', 1),
(2364, 912, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/LTR/Global/Slides/IMG02.svg', 1),
(2365, 912, 2, 'High-Impact Hazards', 1),
(2366, 912, 3, 'Sharing the road with large trucks is more dangerous than many drivers realize. Trucks have large blind spots, and their size makes them difficult to handle in emergency situations. A commercial truck is 20 to 30 times heavier than a passenger vehicle, so when a car and a truck collide, the car usually loses. ', 1),
(2367, 913, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/LTR/Global/Slides/IMG03.svg', 1),
(2368, 913, 2, 'Trucks Are Not Big Cars', 1),
(2369, 913, 3, 'Many drivers make the mistake of treating trucks like big cars, but a trucks size and length make them extreme hazards all drivers should try to avoid. Trucks take longer to stop, are harder to steer, and their large turning radius often forces them far into an intersection or across two lanes. Many car drivers hit by a truck did not respect the trucks size and weight.', 1),
(2370, 914, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/LTR/Global/Slides/IMG04.svg', 1),
(2371, 914, 2, 'Unpredictable Hazards ', 1),
(2372, 914, 3, 'Many of the dangers posed by trucks are out of your control. Truck tires can blow out or their brakes can fail, causing a serious threat for nearby motorists. In bad weather, heavy splash reduces visibility, and air turbulence from a truck can force a nearby car to lose control. \n\nFatigue is another problem for truck drivers. Tiredness is a factor in up to 30% of commercial transport crashes. ', 1),
(2373, 916, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/global/slides/IMG06.svg', 1),
(2374, 916, 2, 'Techniques to Avoid Collisions ', 1),
(2375, 916, 3, 'The best solution to reduce your risk of a collision with a large truck is to avoid them altogether. When you do encounter a large truck on the road, making the truck driver aware of your presence will help keep both of you safe. This means:\n Signaling during lane changes. \n Giving trucks room to complete their maneuvers.\n Checking mirrors and blind spots before passing a truck.\n Staying out of a trucks blind spots.', 1),
(2376, 915, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/LTR/Global/Slides/IMG05.svg', 1),
(2377, 915, 2, 'Who Is at Fault?', 1),
(2378, 915, 3, 'In car-truck collisions, it is often the driver of the smaller vehicle who makes the mistake, such as improper lane changes and disrespecting a trucks large size and blind spots. Car drivers are responsible for the majority of car-truck crashes.   ', 1),
(2379, 917, 12, 'Trucks Stop Slower', 1),
(2380, 917, 14, 'Traveling at 80 km/h, some large trucks take up to 50% longer to stop than a car.', 1),
