(2542, 985, 3, 'Remember these basic rules for driving safely on highways:\n  Observe the speed limit or a lower speed appropriate for the conditions.\n  When entering or exiting, adjust your speed to the traffic flow.\n  Overtake other vehicles on the left.\n  Avoid changing lanes unless necessary, and treat every lane change individually.\n  Maintain sufficient space around your vehicle that others should not enter.', 1),
(2543, 980, 2, 'Safe Highway Driving', 1),
(2544, 980, 3, 'In this module, participants will learn:\n1.  The risks of traveling at high speeds.\n2.  Unsafe driving behaviors to avoid on the highway.\n3.  Techniques to manage highway driving.', 1),
(2545, 981, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/MOT/Global/Slides/IMG02.svg', 1),
(2546, 981, 2, 'Designed to Be Fast', 1),
(2547, 981, 3, 'High speeds are always dangerous, and highways are built to be fast. While smooth turns and the lack of traffic obstructions help ensure motorists travel safely, these same factors can encourage fatigue and inattention, and tempt some drivers to speed. Many people are killed each year on highways in Asia.', 1),
(2548, 982, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/MOT/Global/Slides/IMG03.svg', 1),
(2549, 982, 2, 'Accelerating the Risks', 1),
(2550, 982, 3, 'Small errors can turn vehicles into destructive objects at highway speeds. When drivers oversteer, they increase their risk of losing control, and since it takes longer to stop, they can reach hazards sooner and strike them much harder. Crashing at high speeds can be as destructive to the human body as falling from the ninth floor of a building. ', 1),
(2551, 983, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/MOT/Global/Slides/IMG04.svg', 1),
(2552, 983, 2, 'External Threats', 1),
(2553, 983, 3, 'Highways are dangerous corridors that leave little room for error. Drivers must navigate around larger vehicles, which have large blind spots and sizes that can obstruct motorists view. When roadwork or a collision closes lanes, traffic can build up quickly along with drivers frustrations. For long-distance travelers, the visual monotony, repetitive patterns of passing lane markings and objects, and constant drone of tires can cause some to lose focus or fall asleep.', 1),
(2554, 984, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/MOT/Global/Slides/IMG05.svg', 1),
(2555, 984, 2, 'Deadly Negligence', 1),
(2556, 984, 3, 'Unsafe drivers treat highways no differently from other roads, but the consequences can be far worse. Injuries are more severe at higher speeds, yet some motorists:\n  Fail to signal their intentions. \n  Fail to properly scan the roadway.\n  Make unsafe lane changes or last-minute exits.\n  Follow other drivers too closely or exploit the open road to speed.', 1),
(2557, 985, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/global/slides/IMG06.svg', 1),
(2558, 985, 2, 'Techniques for Safe Highway Driving', 1),
(2559, 986, 12, 'Highways vs. Urban Roads', 1),
(2560, 986, 14, 'The risk of crash injuries at highway speeds is at least 32 times higher than the risk on urban roads.', 1),
