(2902, 1123, 2, 'Prepare for the Unexpected', 1),
(2903, 1118, 3, 'In this module, participants will learn:\n1.    Why rural roads are dangerous.\n2.    Common mistakes drivers make on rural roads.\n3.    Tips for safe driving in the countryside.\n', 1),
(2904, 1123, 3, 'Roads in outlying areas may be hours away from police or emergency services. To be ready for an emergency, keep a full tank of gas and prepare a safety kit that includes:\n First aid supplies.\n Warning triangles and reflective clothing.\n A fully charged mobile phone.\n A road atlas of the area you are in.\n Energy bars, chocolate or caffeinated drinks.\n A blanket.\n Water  both for you and the vehicle''s radiator if the engine overheats.\n Jumper cables and a fire extinguisher.\n A spare tire and a car jack.\n A flashlight.\n', 1),
(2905, 1119, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/RUR/Global/Slides/IMG02.svg', 1),
(2906, 1118, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/RUR/Global/Slides/IMG01.svg', 1),
(2907, 1119, 2, 'Not Designed With Safety in Mind', 1),
(2908, 1119, 3, 'Unlike urban streets and highways, rural roads do not have many of the safety features put in place to keep drivers safe. They lack adequate signage, offer minimal lighting, and are often unpaved and infrequently maintained. The decreased presence of law enforcement may lead to some drivers taking unnecessary risks without fear of consequences. Of all road deaths in Asia, as many as 6 out of 10 happen on rural roads.  ', 1),
(2909, 1120, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/RUR/Global/Slides/IMG03.svg', 1),
(2910, 1120, 2, 'Higher Risk of Crashes ', 1),
(2911, 1120, 3, 'Rural roads often lack signals or other traffic control devices to slow vehicles down. At higher speeds, a rural roads sharp corners and steep slopes become treacherous driving hazards, which is one reason why loss of control accounts for approximately one-third of crashes on major rural roads. ', 1),
(2912, 1121, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/RUR/Global/Slides/IMG04.svg', 1),
(2913, 1121, 2, 'Dangerously Quiet', 1),
(2914, 1121, 3, 'The absence of traffic in outlying areas can give drivers a false sense of security. Rural roads pass through natural habitats, so the threat of an animal strike is constant. Farmers use rural roads to transport goods, and their vehicles can block all or part of the road. Unchanging scenery or absolute darkness at night may lead to drowsiness and inattention. ', 1),
(2915, 1122, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/RUR/Global/Slides/IMG05.svg', 1),
(2916, 1122, 2, 'Fatal Errors', 1),
(2917, 1122, 3, 'Confusion about priority at intersections, unsafe passing and driving too fast for conditions are among the primary errors made by drivers on rural roads. Speeding into a blind curve leaves you unprepared for any number of unknown obstacles, so slow down early and stay to the right. Watch for clouds of dust or flashes of light around sharp turns, as they may indicate the approach of another vehicle ahead. ', 1),
(2918, 1123, 1, '/media/courses/ddt/global/slides/IMG06.svg', 1),
(2919, 1124, 12, 'Higher Risk of Serious Crashes', 1),
(2920, 1124, 14, 'Single-vehicle crashes, head-on collisions and crashes at intersections account for up to 75% of all crashes on rural roads. ', 1),
